The Apollo 8 astronauts returned to Earth on December 27, 1968, when Apollo 8's spacecraft splashed down in the northern Pacific Ocean.
The spaceflight lasted 15 minutes 30 seconds, reached an altitude of more than 102.8 nautical miles (190.4Â km), and flew 262.5 nautical miles (486.2Â km) downrange, landing in the Atlantic Ocean.
Apollo 11 returned to Earth and splashed down in the Pacific Ocean on July 24 after more than eight days in space.
The ascent flight consisted of a Russian commander and two flight engineers from Denmark (ESA) and Kazakhstan respectively.
After three orbits, the spacecraft re-entered the Earth's atmosphere, splashed down in the North Atlantic Ocean, and was safely taken aboard USS Noa.
The astronauts' peril briefly renewed public interest in the Apollo program; tens of millions watched the splashdown in the South Pacific Ocean on television.
